<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt; text-decoration: none;">It’s time to worry, says a new report from the National Research Council. The amount of debris floating in orbit around Earth has been growing exponentially and may have already reached a “tipping point.” </span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">What kind of tipping point? Well, </span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt; text-decoration: none;">in 1978 a NASA scientist named Donald Kessler predicted that, as the amount of space debris grows, it could eventually become dense enough to touch off a “collision cascade.” In that scenario, each collision would generate new debris, causing more debris-generating collisions, until low Earth orbit becomes hopelessly clogged and unusable by spacecraft or even satellites.We’re not there yet, but we could be on our way</span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">, the Washington Post reports. </span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt; text-decoration: none;">A pair of recent collisions has doubled the number of fragments since 2007. There are now an estimated 22,000 hunks of debris large enough for NASA to track individually, and there could be hundreds of thousands or millions more bits that we can’t see.</span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;"> From the Post: </span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt; text-decoration: none;">Active satellites are at risk of damage and “as the amount of debris increases, there will be increases in the cost of operating</span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">” satellites, said Brian Weeden, a technical adviser with the Secure World Foundation, which focuses on space sustainability. </span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt; text-decoration: none;">Manned spacecraft are also in danger. The international space station had a close call in late June, when an unidentified object came within 1,100 feet</span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;"> but caused no damage; astronauts were preemptively evacuated to emergency spacecraft.</span>

